Finance experts have commended President Muhammadu for assenting to the revised 2020 budget of N10.8 trillion expeditiously. The experts, who were united in their view that the COVID-19 pandemic has seriously impacted the nation’s economy, said it was also gratifying that the president acted quickly to mitigate the impact. President Buhari yesterday who signed the revised N10.81trillion budget into law at the presidential villa also ordered that ministries, department and agencies (MDAs) be given 50 per cent of their capital allocation by the end of the month. Applauding the president for the speedy signing of the revised 2020 Appropriation Act, director-general of Lagos Chamber of Commerce and Industry (LCCI), Muda Yusuf, said the prevailing economic condition has caused severe disruptions and delays in many facets of the nation’s national life. He stated that this has also affected federal government’s plan to have a January to December budget cycle. Yusuf  said, “One should acknowledge that exogenous factors were responsible for the delay experienced this time.  The commitment of the government and National Assembly to return the budget cycle to January to December should also be recognized. “The timing of the budget assent will no doubt affect budget implementation, especially the capital component of the budget. Hopefully, the situation will normalise from the next fiscal year.” Also, managing director of APT Securities and Funds Limited, Mallam Kurifi Garuba said looking at the revised budget compared to the initial budget, the difference is not much as to the loss of revenue the federal government is likely to suffer. He said, “The government is looking for borrowed funds to fund the budget. Even in 2019 that we did not experience COVID-19, we could not generate much. “We should not forget that even if the government was able to generate what they intended to, they have a deficit of over N2.3 trillion. Now with COVID-19, the deficit will be much higher.” He called on the government to find ways of reducing the cost of governance to conserve revenue. Speaking in an exclusive interview with LEADERSHIP, executive secretary, Nigerian Council of Registered Insurance Brokers (NCRIB), Mr  FataiAdegbenro, applauded the president for the speedy signing of the 2020 revised budget, stating that this will also ensure that government and its agencies renew their insurances as and when due, thereby, contributing to growth in premium income of the insurance industry. As federal government embarks on capital projects, he said, insurers would equally be able to underwrite, especially those capital intensive projects, He noted that the timely passage of the budget would lead to rapid economic transformation and growth, while ensuring that government has more time to provide the needed infrastructure that will lead the country to its promise land.  Meanwhile, President Buhari while signing the revised 2020 budget recalled that he had signed the 2020 Appropriation Act into law on Tuesday, December 17, 2019. He however pointed out that it became necessary to revise the Appropriation Act 2020 in response to recent developments, particularly the COVID-19 pandemic. He further explained that crude prices in the world market had declined sharply from a high of $72.20 per barrel in January 2020 to below $20 per barrel in April 2020, and have since remained around $40 per barrel. He said, “Nigeria’s crude oil production quota has been reduced as part of the efforts of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to strengthen the oil market. Global trade has generally been disrupted as almost all economies were locked down for protracted periods in the wake of the COVID-19 Pandemic. “All these developments are plunging the global economy into recession, and Nigeria has not escaped the impact of this. In effect, the assumptions underlying the 2020 Appropriation Act are no longer sustainable. “It is therefore imperative to adjust our expected revenues, considering the widespread disruptions in domestic and international economic activities due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, and the containment measures taken in response thereto. “Understandably too, we needed to reallocate resources in the Appropriation (Repeal and Amendment) Act, 2020 to ensure effective implementation of required health and emergency measures, as well as to mitigate the negative socio-economic effects of the COVID-19 Pandemic”. Buhari further noted that the 2020 amended budget underscores his administration’s firm commitment to effectively contain the spread of COVID-19 and protect the lives and livelihood of Nigerians. He continued: “With  these budget amendments, as well as our recently launched N2.3 trillion Stimulus Programme, we are well-positioned to safeguard the economy. “Considering recent budget implementation challenges, I have directed that efforts be made to ensure effective implementation of the Appropriation (Repeal and Amendment) Act, 2020 in order to realise its laudable objectives”. Accordingly, the president directed that all ministers are to ensure that their departments and agencies intensify capital project delivery efforts and fully cooperate with the ministry of Finance, Budget and National Planning to achieve the laudable objectives of the budget. He stated, “We have, nevertheless, made some progress in the implementation of the Appropriation Act 2020. As at 31st May 2020, the sum of N253.33billion has been released for the implementation of capital projects. “The Federal Ministry of Finance, Budget and National Planning is in the process of effecting budgetary releases that will ensure that all Ministries, Departments and Agencies receive at least 50 per cent of their amended capital budgets by the end of this month. “The Appropriation (Repeal and Amendment) Act, 2020 that I have just signed into law provides for aggregate expenditures of N10.81 trillion, which is an increase of N216 billion over the level of expenditure initially proposed in the 2020 Appropriation Act. The Honourable Minister of Finance, Budget and National Planning will provide further details of the 2020 Amended Budget”.  FG Releases N3.52trn In 5 Months  Although President Buhari has signed the revised 2020 budget of N10.8trn into law, minister of Finance, Budget and National Planning, Hajiya Zainab Ahmed, yesterday disclosed that N3.52 trillion had been released to finance the budget between January and May, 2020. She said of May ending, the federal government’s retained revenue was N1.48trn, 56 per cent of target revenue for the entire budget. The Minister spoke during the presentation of the draft 2021-2023 Medium Term Expenditure Framework (MTEF)/FSP at a consultative forum. The performance of the 2020 budget parameters shows that GDP growth, oil production and inflation fell below target. On the expenditure side, N9.97trn was appropriated (excluding government owned enterprises and project-tied loans), while N3.52trn, representing 84.8% of the prorate N4.16trn, was spent. Of the expenditure, N1.25trillion was for debt service, and N1.32trn for personnel cost, including pensions. According to the Finance minister, additional N100billion was released for capital expenses in June, bringing the total amount for capital expenditure to N353.33billion. She said overall, the 2020 revised budget shows an increase of N301bn over the amount proposed by President Buhari. She gave a breakdown of the difference of N301billion as follows: 10 per cent cuts in allocations to Statutory Transfer Agencies and arms of government were reinstated by the National Assembly N25.53bn; increase in contingency provision in service wide votes by N12.5bn and N185.9bn Federation intervention included in FGN budget. “There is also N4bn hazard allowance for health workers; N3bn for social housing. Other adjustments amount to N70bn. We have revised the 2020 FGN budget and will accelerate implementation to maintain budget process credibility, enhance GDP growth and promote social inclusion,” Ahmed added. She continued: “An overview of the 2021-2023 MTEF shows an aggregate projected FGN expenditure for 2021 is N11.86trn in the 2021 outlook. Aggregate projected revenue from available sources for 2021 is N698trn, resulting in a N5.16 fiscal deficit for 2021. “The 2021-2023 MTEF/FSP is the pre-budget statement that provides the framework for the development of the 2021 budget. It is being framed against the backdrop of a challenging global economic environment as well as domestic factors. We aim to keep the deficit within the 3% ceiling over the medium term, and are therefore working on identifying new revenue sources and/or cost reductions. “Under the 2021-2023 MTEF, oil GDP is expected to contract by 12.96 per cent in 2020, year on year, causing an economy-wide drag resulting in slower growth in non-oil GDP by-3.6 per cent, year on year. Based on this, real GDP is expected to decline by 4.2 per cent in 2020. “The nominal GDP is expected to increase from N130,836.1billion in 2020 to N132,125.4bn in 2021 and then up to N138,415.8bn in 2023. “Similarly, consumption expenditure is projected to stay flat at N118,735.2bn in 2020 and N118,468.7bn in 2021 and grow to N124,358.5bn by 2023, reflecting a gradual steadiness in the recovery. “Inflation, however, is expected to remain above single digit over the medium term, given the structural issues impacting on cost of doing business, including high cost of food distribution”.